The most visible development was the president\'92s decision to treat Washington, D.C., as a stage for emergency rule. Over several days, he declared a crime emergency in the District, announced that he was taking control of the Metropolitan Police Department, and ordered the deployment of National Guard troops and federal agents into the city\'92s streets. This was done despite local statistics showing that violent crime had fallen to a thirty-year low. The White House framed the capital as \'93lawless\'94 and \'93out of control,\'94 and used that framing to invoke a clause in the D.C. Home Rule Act that allows temporary federal control of the police. In practice, this meant that local officers, who normally answer to the mayor and city council, were placed under federal direction for thirty days, with the president and attorney general empowered to direct their use for \'93federal purposes.\'94 The effect was to convert a routine public safety issue into a pretext for centralizing coercive power in the hands of the executive.\
