The deployment itself was heavy. Roughly 800 National Guard members and hundreds of federal officers from the FBI, DEA, ATF, and other agencies were sent into the District. The president ordered them to sweep homeless encampments, clear streets, and make arrests under the banner of restoring order. He had already threatened to force homeless residents to leave the city or face eviction, promising to use federal officers to carry out his demand. The emergency order delegated authority to the attorney general to direct the D.C. mayor to provide police services as needed, effectively subordinating local command to federal priorities. This was more than a show of force. It was a practical test of how far the executive could stretch emergency powers to override local governance without immediate, decisive pushback from other branches.\
