There was resistance, and it mattered. The D.C. attorney general filed suit against the administration, arguing that the takeover violated the District\'92s right to self-governance and exceeded the conditions laid out in the Home Rule Act. Democratic members of Congress, led by Representative Jamie Raskin and Delegate Eleanor Holmes Norton, introduced a joint resolution to end the federalization, asserting that the statutory requirements for such a move had not been met. Behind the scenes, city lawyers and White House officials negotiated. By week\'92s end, they reached an agreement to scale back the order: the Metropolitan Police Department would remain under the control of its chief, Pamela Smith, rather than being placed under a DEA official. The administration retained the ability to use local police for federal purposes in emergencies, but the most blatant form of direct federal command was checked. This partial rollback did not erase the week\'92s damage, yet it showed that coordinated legal and political pressure could still force the White House to retreat from its most aggressive claims.\
